@wangqiang1588  Thanks for the report. I’m unable to reproduce the issue with the current code sample, as my local result looks like this:

<img width="500" height="250" alt="Image" src="https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/f4a60642-4ce1-4e6a-8543-71867bbb3e82" />


Could you share a self-contained MRE and the exact steps you're taking to trigger the bug? If you're seeing any specific errors in the console, please paste those here as well so I can take a closer look.

After initial investigation my assesment is that the reason why this happens is that both Flutter and WebKit are processing keyboard events asynchronously. Asynchronous keyboard events in AppKit are a bit of a hack - you process the event, and then when unhandled you pass it to next responder. The problem here is that because it's asynchronous, AppKit loses track and when the re-dispatched event reaches NSWindow, it gets sent to first responder again. Webkit has a guard against this:

https://github.com/WebKit/WebKit/blob/a6b12b5049f2a3333697882d485ea0df37b73be4/Source/WebKit/UIProcess/mac/WebViewImpl.mm#L5447-L5452
```cpp
    m_keyDownEventBeingResent = event;
    [NSApp _setCurrentEvent:event];
    [NSApp sendEvent:event];
    m_keyDownEventBeingResent = nullptr;
```

The problem here is that we also have asynchronous event dispatch. When webkit is done, we send the event to framework, asynchronously receive it and redispatch it. When this redispatch happens `m_keyDownEventBeingResent` is already `null` so once `NSWindow` sends the event to first responder (webkit), it processes as at if it was new.

